## 1. Purpose

This document defines basic usage guidelines for OPRMT™ brand references, framework naming, visual presentation, attribution, repository documentation, and public-facing materials.

The purpose of this guide is to preserve consistency, prevent misrepresentation, and protect the integrity of the OPRMT™ Framework.

---

## 2. Brand Identity

OPRMT™ should be presented as a structured prompt engineering framework created by Michael W. Fleming.

Correct positioning:

```text
OPRMT™ is a structured prompt engineering framework for designing clearer, repeatable, auditable AI instructions.
```

Do not present OPRMT™ as:

- Public-domain content
- A casual prompting trick
- A guaranteed outcome system
- A legally recognized certification authority unless verified
- An accredited academic institution unless verified
- A framework owned by another person or organization

---

## 3. Official Name Usage

Preferred usage:

```text
OPRMT™
OPRMT™ Framework
The OPRMT™ Framework
OPRMT™ structured prompt framework
```

Avoid:

```text
oprmt
O.P.R.M.T.
OPRMT Method Thing
OPRMT Formula
OPRMT AI Hack
```

Use the trademark symbol on first prominent use in a document or page where practical:

```text
OPRMT™
```

After first use, `OPRMT` may be used where formatting constraints require it, but official documents should prefer `OPRMT™`.

---

## 4. Component Naming

Use the official component sequence:

```text
O — Objective
P — Parameters
R — Results
M — Method
T — Tools
```

Do not rename components without an approved standard change request.

Avoid:

```text
O — Outcome
P — Prompt
R — Response
M — Model
T — Text
```

These alternatives conflict with the controlled OPRMT™ component structure.

---

## 5. Ownership Attribution

Use clear attribution when referencing OPRMT™ publicly.

Short attribution:

```text
OPRMT™ Framework created by Michael W. Fleming.
```

Extended attribution:

```text
This material references the OPRMT™ Framework, created by Michael W. Fleming. OPRMT™ and related framework materials remain the property of their owner unless otherwise stated in the repository license, notice, or usage policy.
```

Repository documents should preserve ownership notices unless a maintainer-approved replacement notice exists.

