## 9. Logo and Mark Usage

If official logo files are added to the repository, they should be stored under:

```text
assets/brand/logo/
```

Recommended future files:

```text
assets/brand/logo/OPRMT-Logo-Primary.svg
assets/brand/logo/OPRMT-Logo-White.svg
assets/brand/logo/OPRMT-Logo-Mark.svg
assets/brand/LOGO_USAGE.md
```

General logo rules:

- Do not distort the logo.
- Do not recolor the logo outside approved brand colors.
- Do not place the logo on low-contrast backgrounds.
- Do not use the logo to imply authorization without permission.
- Do not remove ownership or attribution notices.
- Do not combine the logo with third-party marks in a way that implies partnership without approval.

---

## 10. Documentation Usage

Official repository documentation should:

- Use clear Markdown structure.
- Include ownership notice.
- Include document type, version, status, and recommended path where appropriate.
- Avoid unsupported claims.
- Preserve official terminology.
- Use file paths in code formatting.
- Use tables for structured information.
- Use code blocks for templates, prompts, file trees, and YAML.
- Avoid excessive inline HTML unless needed.

---

## 11. Prompt Asset Usage

Prompt assets should be structured using OPRMT™ where appropriate.

A repository-ready prompt asset should include:

```text
Prompt ID:
Prompt Name:
Category:
Version:
Status:
Objective:
Parameters:
Results:
Method:
Tools:
Compliance Notes:
Ownership Notice:
```

Do not submit prompt assets that:

- Claim guaranteed outcomes
- Claim legal compliance without review
- Claim medical, financial, or legal authority
- Include copied third-party proprietary content
- Remove OPRMT™ ownership references
- Misrepresent the framework or its owner

---

## 12. Commercial Use Guidance

Commercial use is not automatically granted by repository visibility.

Before using OPRMT™ materials commercially, review:

```text
LICENSE.md
NOTICE.md
legal/COMMERCIAL_USE_GUIDANCE.md
legal/USAGE_POLICY.md
legal/COMMERCIAL_USE_POLICY.md
```

Commercial uses that may require permission include:

- Selling OPRMT™ prompt packs
- Selling derivative training materials
- Redistributing repository files in paid products
- White-labeling OPRMT™ as another framework
- Using OPRMT™ branding in paid client deliverables
- Claiming official certification or instructor status

---

## 13. Certification and Authority Claims

Do not claim:

```text
Official OPRMT™ Certified
Authorized OPRMT™ Instructor
OPRMT™ Accredited Program
Certified by OPRMT™
Official OPRMT™ Training Partner
```

unless explicitly approved in writing.

Do not claim that OPRMT™ guarantees:

- Employment
- Income
- Legal compliance
- Business results
- AI accuracy
- Accreditation
- Professional licensing
- Universal success rates

---

## 14. Public Reference Rules

When referencing OPRMT™ publicly:

Do:

- Use the correct name.
- Attribute Michael W. Fleming.
- Link to official materials when available.
- Preserve the official OPRMT™ sequence.
- Make clear when your work is independent.

Do not:

- Imply official approval without permission.
- Remove ownership notices.
- Rebrand the framework.
- Sell copied materials without permission.
- Claim certification authority without approval.

---

## 15. Repository Contribution Rules

When contributing brand-related files:

- Use approved colors.
- Use approved typography.
- Preserve ownership notices.
- Follow repository naming conventions.
- Add metadata to major files.
- Update relevant indexes.
- Submit changes through pull request review.
- Link any controlled terminology change to a standard change request.

